# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: protein-nmr
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] In nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy, the **chemical shift** is the resonant frequency of an atomic nucleus relative to a standard in a magnetic field.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Often the position and number of chemical shifts are diagnostic of the structure of a molecule.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Chemical shifts are also used to describe signals in other forms of spectroscopy such as photoemission spectroscopy.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Some atomic nuclei possess a magnetic moment (nuclear spin), which gives rise to different energy levels and resonance frequencies in a magnetic field.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] The total magnetic field experienced by a nucleus includes local magnetic fields induced by currents of electrons in the molecular orbitals (electrons have a magnetic moment themselves).
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] The electron distribution of the same type of nucleus (e.g.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] 1H, 13C, 15N) usually varies according to the local geometry (binding partners, bond lengths, angles between bonds, and so on), and with it the local magnetic field at each nucleus.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] This is reflected in the spin energy levels (and resonance frequencies).
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] The variations of nuclear magnetic resonance frequencies of the same kind of nucleus, due to variations in the electron distribution, is called the chemical shift.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] The size of the chemical shift is given with respect to a reference frequency or reference sample (see also chemical shift referencing), usually a molecule with a barely distorted electron distribution.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] where *B*0 is the induction of the magnet (SI units of tesla), and $\gamma$ is the magnetogyric ratio of the nucleus — an empirically measured fundamental constant determined by the details of the structure of each nucleus.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] MRI scanners are often referred to by their field strengths *B*0 (e.g.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] "a 7 T scanner"), whereas NMR spectrometers are commonly referred to by the corresponding proton Larmor frequency (e.g.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] "a 300 MHz spectrometer", which has a *B*0 of 7 T).
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] While chemical shift is referenced in order that the units are equivalent across different field strengths, the actual frequency separation in hertz scales with field strength (*B*0).
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] As a result, the difference of chemical shift between two signals (ppm) represents a larger number of hertz on machines that have larger *B*0, and therefore the signals are less likely to be overlapping in the resulting spectrum.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] This increased resolution is a significant advantage for analysis.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Higher-field machines are also favoured on account of having intrinsically higher signal arising from the Boltzmann distribution of magnetic spin states.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] where *ν*sample is the absolute resonance frequency of the sample, and *ν*ref is the absolute resonance frequency of a standard reference compound, measured in the same applied magnetic field *B*0.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Since the numerator is usually expressed in hertz, and the denominator in megahertz, δ is expressed in ppm.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] The detected frequencies (in Hz) for 1H, 13C, and 29Si nuclei are usually referenced against TMS (tetramethylsilane), TSP (trimethylsilylpropanoic acid), or DSS, which by the definition above have a chemical shift of zero if chosen as the reference.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Other standard materials are used for setting the chemical shift for other nuclei.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Although the absolute resonance frequency depends on the applied magnetic field, the chemical shift is independent of external magnetic field strength.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] On the other hand, the resolution of NMR will increase with applied magnetic field.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] In early proton NMR publications, the τ scale was also used, defined as τ = 10 ppm - δTMS.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Practically speaking, diverse methods may be used to reference chemical shifts in an NMR experiment, which can be subdivided into *indirect* and *direct* referencing methods.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Indirect referencing uses a channel other than the one of interest to adjust chemical shift scale correctly, i.e. the solvent signal in the deuterium (lock) channel can be used to reference the a 1H NMR spectrum.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] **External referencing**, involving sample and reference contained separately in coaxial cylindrical tubes.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] With this procedure, the reference signal is still visible in the spectrum of interest, although the reference and the sample are physically separated by a glass wall.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Magnetic susceptibility differences between the sample and the reference phase need to be corrected theoretically, which lowers the practicality of this procedure.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] **Substitution method**: The use of separate cylindrical tubes for the sample and the reference compound, with (in principle) spectra recorded individually for each.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Similar to external referencing, this method allows referencing without sample contamination.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] If field/frequency locking via the 2H signal of the deuterated solvent is used and the solvents of reference and analyte are the same, the use of this methods is straightforward.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Problems may arise if different solvents are used for the reference compound and the sample as (just like for external referencing) magnetic susceptibility differences need to be corrected theoretically.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] If this method is used without field/frequency locking, shimming procedures between the sample and the reference need to be avoided as they change the applied magnetic field (and thereby influence the chemical shift).
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] This system, however, relies on accurately determined 2H NMR chemical shifts enlisted in the spectrometer software and correctly determined Ξ values by IUPAC.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] A recent study for 19F NMR spectroscopy revealed that the use of the absolute scale and lock-based internal referencing led to errors in chemical shifts.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] These may be negated by inclusion of calibrated reference compounds.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] The electrons around a nucleus will circulate in a magnetic field and create a secondary induced magnetic field.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] This field opposes the applied field as stipulated by Lenz's law and atoms with higher induced fields (i.e., higher electron density) are therefore called *shielded*, relative to those with lower electron density.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Electron-donating alkyl groups, for example, lead to increased shielding whereas electron-withdrawing substituents such as nitro groups lead to *deshielding* of the nucleus.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Not only substituents cause local induced fields.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Bonding electrons can also lead to shielding and deshielding effects.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] A striking example of this is the pi bonds in benzene.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Circular current through the hyperconjugated system causes a shielding effect at the molecule's center and a deshielding effect at its edges.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Trends in chemical shift are explained based on the degree of shielding or deshielding.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Nuclei are found to resonate in a wide range to the left (or more rare to the right) of the internal standard.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Conversely a lower chemical shift is called a **diamagnetic shift**, and is **upfield** and more shielded.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] In real molecules protons are surrounded by a cloud of charge due to adjacent bonds and atoms.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] In an applied magnetic field (**B**0) electrons circulate and produce an induced field (**B**i) which opposes the applied field.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] The effective field at the nucleus will be **B** = **B**0 − **B**i.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] The nucleus is said to be experiencing a diamagnetic shielding.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Important factors influencing chemical shift are electron density, electronegativity of neighboring groups and anisotropic induced magnetic field effects.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Electron density shields a nucleus from the external field.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] For example, in proton NMR the electron-poor tropylium ion has its protons downfield at 9.17 ppm, those of the electron-rich cyclooctatetraenyl anion move upfield to 6.75 ppm and its dianion even more upfield to 5.56 ppm.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] A nucleus in the vicinity of an electronegative atom experiences reduced electron density and the nucleus is therefore deshielded.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] In proton NMR of methyl halides (CH3X) the chemical shift of the methyl protons increase in the order I < Br < Cl < F from 2.16 ppm to 4.26 ppm reflecting this trend.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] In carbon NMR the chemical shift of the carbon nuclei increase in the same order from around −10 ppm to 70 ppm.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Also when the electronegative atom is removed further away the effect diminishes until it can be observed no longer.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Anisotropic induced magnetic field effects are the result of a local induced magnetic field experienced by a nucleus resulting from circulating electrons that can either be paramagnetic when it is parallel to the applied field or diamagnetic when it is opposed to it.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] It is observed in alkenes where the double bond is oriented perpendicular to the external field with pi electrons likewise circulating at right angles.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] The induced magnetic field lines are parallel to the external field at the location of the alkene protons which therefore shift downfield to a 4.5 ppm to 7.5 ppm range.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] The three-dimensional space where a diamagnetic shift is called the shielding zone with a cone-like shape aligned with the external field.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] The protons in aromatic compounds are shifted downfield even further with a signal for benzene at 7.73 ppm as a consequence of a diamagnetic ring current.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Alkyne protons by contrast resonate at high field in a 2–3 ppm range.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] For alkynes the most effective orientation is the external field in parallel with electrons circulation around the triple bond.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] In this way the acetylenic protons are located in the cone-shaped shielding zone hence the upfield shift.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] 1H and 13C are not the only nuclei susceptible to NMR experiments.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] In general, the associated increased signal-to-noise and resolution has driven a move towards increasingly high field strengths.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] In limited cases, however, lower fields are preferred; examples are for systems in chemical exchange, where the speed of the exchange relative to the NMR experiment can cause additional and confounding linewidth broadening.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Similarly, while avoidance of second order coupling is generally preferred, this information can be useful for elucidation of chemical structures.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Using refocussing pulses placed between recording of successive points of the free induction decay, in an analogous fashion to the spin echo technique in MRI, the chemical shift evolution can be scaled to provide apparent low-field spectra on a high-field spectrometer.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] In a similar fashion, it is possible to upscale the effect of J-coupling relative to the chemical shift using pulse sequences that include additional J-coupling evolution periods interspersed with conventional spin evolutions.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] The Knight shift (first reported in 1949) and Shoolery's rule are observed with pure metals and methylene groups, respectively.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] The NMR chemical shift in its present-day meaning first appeared in journals in 1950.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] Chemical shifts with a different meaning appear in X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy as the shift in atomic core-level energy due to a specific chemical environment.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] The term is also used in Mössbauer spectroscopy, where similarly to NMR it refers to a shift in peak position due to the local chemical bonding environment.
[src:protein-nmr/chemical-shift] As is the case for NMR the chemical shift reflects the electron density at the atomic nucleus.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] NMR involves the quantum-mechanical properties of the central core ("nucleus") of the atom.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] These properties depend on the local molecular environment, and their measurement provides a map of how the atoms are linked chemically, how close they are in space, and how rapidly they move with respect to each other.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] This change of scale requires much higher sensitivity of detection and stability for long term measurement.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] In contrast to MRI, structural biology studies do not directly generate an image, but rely on complex computer calculations to generate three-dimensional molecular models.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Currently most samples are examined in a solution in water, but methods are being developed to also work with solid samples.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Data collection relies on placing the sample inside a powerful magnet, sending radio frequency signals through the sample, and measuring the absorption of those signals.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Depending on the environment of atoms within the protein, the nuclei of individual atoms will absorb different frequencies of radio signals.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Furthermore, the absorption signals of different nuclei may be perturbed by adjacent nuclei.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] This information can be used to determine the distance between nuclei.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] These distances in turn can be used to determine the overall structure of the protein.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] A typical study might involve how two proteins interact with each other, possibly with a view to developing small molecules that can be used to probe the normal biology of the interaction ("chemical biology") or to provide possible leads for pharmaceutical use (drug development).
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Frequently, the interacting pair of proteins may have been identified by studies of human genetics, indicating the interaction can be disrupted by unfavorable mutations, or they may play a key role in the normal biology of a "model" organism like the fruit fly, yeast, the worm *C. elegans*, or mice.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] To prepare a sample, methods of molecular biology are typically used to make quantities of protein by recombinant expression and purification from bacteria.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] This also permits changing the isotopic composition of the molecule, which is desirable because the isotopes behave differently and provide methods for identifying overlapping NMR signals.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Protein nuclear magnetic resonance is performed on aqueous samples of highly purified protein.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Usually, the sample consists of between 300 and 600 microlitres with a protein concentration in the range 0.1 – 3 millimolar.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The source of the protein can be either natural or produced in a production system using recombinant DNA techniques through genetic engineering.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Recombinantly expressed proteins are usually easier to produce in sufficient quantity, and this method makes isotopic labeling possible.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The purified protein is usually dissolved in a buffer solution and adjusted to the desired solvent conditions.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The NMR sample is prepared in a thin-walled glass tube.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Protein NMR utilizes multidimensional nuclear magnetic resonance experiments to obtain information about the protein.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Ideally, each distinct nucleus in the molecule experiences a distinct electronic environment and thus has a distinct chemical shift by which it can be recognized.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] However, in large molecules such as proteins the number of resonances can typically be several thousand and a one-dimensional spectrum inevitably has incidental overlaps.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Therefore, multidimensional experiments that correlate the frequencies of distinct nuclei are performed.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The additional dimensions decrease the chance of overlap and have a larger information content, since they correlate signals from nuclei within a specific part of the molecule.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Magnetization is transferred into the sample using pulses of electromagnetic (radiofrequency) energy and between nuclei using delays; the process is described with so-called pulse sequences.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Pulse sequences allow the experimenter to investigate and select specific types of connections between nuclei.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The array of nuclear magnetic resonance experiments used on proteins fall in two main categories — one where magnetization is transferred through the chemical bonds, and one where the transfer is through space, irrespective of the bonding structure.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The first category is used to assign the different chemical shifts to a specific nucleus, and the second is primarily used to generate the distance restraints used in the structure calculation, and in the assignment with unlabelled protein.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Other things being equal, higher-dimensional experiments will take longer than lower-dimensional experiments.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Typically, the first experiment to be measured with an isotope-labelled protein is a 2D heteronuclear single quantum correlation (HSQC) spectrum, where "heteronuclear" refers to nuclei other than 1H.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] In theory, the heteronuclear single quantum correlation has one peak for each H bound to a heteronucleus.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Thus, in the 15N-HSQC, with a 15N labelled protein, one signal is expected for each nitrogen atom in the back bone, with the exception of proline, which has no amide-hydrogen due to the cyclic nature of its backbone.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Additional 15N-HSQC signals are contributed by each residue with a nitrogen-hydrogen bond in its side chain (W, N, Q, R, H, K).
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The 15N-HSQC is often referred to as the fingerprint of a protein because each protein has a unique pattern of signal positions.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Analysis of the 15N-HSQC allows researchers to evaluate whether the expected number of peaks is present and thus to identify possible problems due to multiple conformations or sample heterogeneity.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The relatively quick heteronuclear single quantum correlation experiment helps determine the feasibility of doing subsequent longer, more expensive, and more elaborate experiments.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] It is not possible to assign peaks to specific atoms from the heteronuclear single quantum correlation alone.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] In order to analyze the nuclear magnetic resonance data, it is important to get a resonance assignment for the protein, that is to find out which chemical shift corresponds to which atom.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] This is typically achieved by sequential walking using information derived from several different types of NMR experiment.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The exact procedure depends on whether the protein is isotopically labelled or not, since a lot of the assignment experiments depend on carbon-13 and nitrogen-15.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] A two-dimensional nuclear magnetic resonance experiment produces a two-dimensional spectrum.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The units of both axes are chemical shifts.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The COSY and TOCSY transfer magnetization through the chemical bonds between adjacent protons.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Thus in a conventional correlation spectroscopy, an alpha proton transfers magnetization to the beta protons, the beta protons transfers to the alpha and gamma protons, if any are present, then the gamma proton transfers to the beta and the delta protons, and the process continues.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] In total correlation spectroscopy, the alpha and all the other protons are able to transfer magnetization to the beta, gamma, delta, epsilon if they are connected by a continuous chain of protons.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The continuous chain of protons are the sidechain of the individual amino acids.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Thus these two experiments are used to build so called spin systems, that is build a list of resonances of the chemical shift of the peptide proton, the alpha protons and all the protons from each residue’s sidechain.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Which chemical shifts corresponds to which nuclei in the spin system is determined by the conventional correlation spectroscopy connectivities and the fact that different types of protons have characteristic chemical shifts.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] To connect the different spinsystems in a sequential order, the nuclear Overhauser effect spectroscopy experiment has to be used.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Because this experiment transfers magnetization through space, it will show crosspeaks for all protons that are close in space regardless of whether they are in the same spin system or not.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The neighbouring residues are inherently close in space, so the assignments can be made by the peaks in the NOESY with other spin systems.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] One important problem using homonuclear nuclear magnetic resonance is overlap between peaks.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] This occurs when different protons have the same or very similar chemical shifts.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] This problem becomes greater as the protein becomes larger, so homonuclear nuclear magnetic resonance is usually restricted to small proteins or peptides.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The most commonly performed 15N experiment is the 1H-15N HSQC.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The experiment is highly sensitive and therefore can be performed relatively quickly.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] It is often used to check the suitability of a protein for structure determination using NMR, as well as for the optimization of the sample conditions.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] It is one of the standard suite of experiments used for the determination of the solution structure of protein.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The HSQC can be further expanded into three- and four dimensional NMR experiments, such as 15N-TOCSY-HSQC and 15N-NOESY-HSQC.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] When the protein is labelled with carbon-13 and nitrogen-15 it is possible to record triple resonance experiments that transfer magnetisation over the peptide bond, and thus connect different spin systems through bonds.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] This is usually done using some of the following experiments, HNCO, HN(CA)CO}, HNCA, HN(CO)CA, HNCACB and CBCA(CO)NH.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] All six experiments consist of a 1H-15N plane (similar to a HSQC spectrum) expanded with a carbon dimension.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] In the HN(CA)CO, each HN plane contains the peaks from the carbonyl carbon from its residue as well the preceding one in the sequence.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The HNCO contains the carbonyl carbon chemical shift from only the preceding residue, but is much more sensitive than HN(CA)CO.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] These experiments allow each 1H-15N peak to be linked to the preceding carbonyl carbon, and sequential assignment can then be undertaken by matching the shifts of each spin system's own and previous carbons.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The HNCA and HN(CO)CA works similarly, just with the alpha carbons (Cα) rather than the carbonyls, and the HNCACB and the CBCA(CO)NH contains both the alpha carbon and the beta carbon (Cβ).
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Usually several of these experiments are required to resolve overlap in the carbon dimension.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] This procedure is usually less ambiguous than the NOESY-based method since it is based on through bond transfer.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] In the NOESY-based methods, additional peaks corresponding to atoms that are close in space but that do not belong to sequential residues will appear, confusing the assignment process.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Following the initial sequential resonance assignment, it is usually possible to extend the assignment from the Cα and Cβ to the rest of the sidechain using experiments such as HCCH-TOCSY, which is basically a TOCSY experiment resolved in an additional carbon dimension.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] In order to make structure calculations, a number of experimentally determined restraints have to be generated.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] These fall into different categories; the most widely used are distance restraints and angle restraints.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] A crosspeak in a NOESY experiment signifies spatial proximity between the two nuclei in question.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Thus each peak can be converted into a maximum distance between the nuclei, usually between 1.8 and 6 angstroms.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The intensity of a NOESY peak is proportional to the distance to the minus 6th power, so the distance is determined according to the intensity of the peak.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The intensity-distance relationship is not exact, so usually a distance range is used.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] It is of great importance to assign the NOESY peaks to the correct nuclei based on the chemical shifts.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] If this task is performed manually it is usually very labor-intensive, since proteins usually have thousands of NOESY peaks.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Some computer programs such as PASD/XPLOR-NIH, UNIO, CYANA, ARIA/CNS, and AUDANA/PONDEROSA-C/S in the Integrative NMR platform perform this task automatically on manually pre-processed listings of peak positions and peak volumes, coupled to a structure calculation.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] To obtain as accurate assignments as possible, it is a great advantage to have access to carbon-13 and nitrogen-15 NOESY experiments, since they help to resolve overlap in the proton dimension.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] This leads to faster and more reliable assignments, and in turn to better structures.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] In addition to distance restraints, restraints on the torsion angles of the chemical bonds, typically the psi and phi angles, can be generated.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] One approach is to use the Karplus equation, to generate angle restraints from coupling constants.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Another approach uses the chemical shifts to generate angle restraints.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Both methods use the fact that the geometry around the alpha carbon affects the coupling constants and chemical shifts, so given the coupling constants or the chemical shifts, a qualified guess can be made about the torsion angles.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The analyte molecules in a sample can be partially ordered with respect to the external magnetic field of the spectrometer by manipulating the sample conditions.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Common techniques include addition of bacteriophages or bicelles to the sample, or preparation of the sample in a stretched polyacrylamide gel.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] This creates a local environment that favours certain orientations of nonspherical molecules.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Normally in solution NMR the dipolar couplings between nuclei are averaged out because of the fast tumbling of the molecule.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The slight overpopulation of one orientation means that a residual dipolar coupling remains to be observed.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The dipolar coupling is commonly used in solid state NMR and provides information about the relative orientation of the bond vectors relative to a single global reference frame.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Typically the orientation of the N-H vector is probed in an HSQC-like experiment.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Initially, residual dipolar couplings were used for refinement of previously determined structures, but attempts at de novo structure determination have also been made.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Thus, it can distinguish between hydrogen and deuterium.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The amide protons in the protein exchange readily with the solvent, and, if the solvent contains a different isotope, typically deuterium, the reaction can be monitored by NMR spectroscopy.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] How rapidly a given amide exchanges reflects its solvent accessibility.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Thus amide exchange rates can give information on which parts of the protein are buried, hydrogen-bonded, etc.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] A common application is to compare the exchange of a free form versus a complex.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The amides that become protected in the complex, are assumed to be in the interaction interface.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The experimentally determined restraints can be used as input for the structure calculation process.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Researchers, using computer programs such as XPLOR-NIH, CYANA, GeNMR, or RosettaNMR attempt to satisfy as many of the restraints as possible, in addition to general properties of proteins such as bond lengths and angles.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The algorithms convert the restraints and the general protein properties into energy terms, and then try to minimize this energy.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The process results in an ensemble of structures that, if the data were sufficient to dictate a certain fold, will converge.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The ensemble of structures obtained is an "experimental model", i.e., a representation of certain kind of experimental data.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] To acknowledge this fact is important because it means that the model could be a good or bad representation of that experimental data.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] In general, the quality of a model will depend on both the quantity and quality of experimental data used to generate it and the correct interpretation of such data.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Random errors will affect the reproducibility and precision of the resulting structures.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] If the errors are systematic, the accuracy of the model will be affected.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The precision indicates the degree of reproducibility of the measurement and is often expressed as the variance of the measured data set under the same conditions.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The accuracy, however, indicates the degree to which a measurement approaches its "true" value.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Ideally, a model of a protein will be more accurate the more fit the actual molecule that represents and will be more precise as there is less uncertainty about the positions of their atoms.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] In practice there is no "standard molecule" against which to compare models of proteins, so the accuracy of a model is given by the degree of agreement between the model and a set of experimental data.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Historically, the structures determined by NMR have been, in general, of lower quality than those determined by X-ray diffraction.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] This is due, in part, to the lower amount of information contained in data obtained by NMR.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Because of this fact, it has become common practice to establish the quality of NMR ensembles, by comparing it against the unique conformation determined by X-ray diffraction, for the same protein.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] However, the X-ray diffraction structure may not exist, and, since the proteins in solution are flexible molecules, a protein represented by a single structure may lead to underestimate the intrinsic variation of the atomic positions of a protein.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] A set of conformations, determined by NMR or X-ray crystallography may be a better representation of the experimental data of a protein than a unique conformation.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The utility of a model will be given, at least in part, by the degree of accuracy and precision of the model.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] An accurate model with relatively poor precision could be useful to study the evolutionary relationships between the structures of a set of proteins, whereas the rational drug design requires both precise and accurate models.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] A model that is not accurate, regardless of the degree of precision with which it was obtained will not be very useful.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Since protein structures are experimental models that can contain errors, it is very important to be able to detect these errors.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The process aimed at the detection of errors is known as validation.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] There are several methods to validate structures, some are statistical like PROCHECK and WHAT IF while others are based on physical principles as CheShift, or a mixture of statistical and physics principles PSVS.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] In addition to structures, nuclear magnetic resonance can yield information on the dynamics of various parts of the protein.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] This usually involves measuring relaxation times such as T1 and T2 to determine order parameters, correlation times, and chemical exchange rates.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] NMR relaxation is a consequence of local fluctuating magnetic fields within a molecule.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Local fluctuating magnetic fields are generated by molecular motions.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] In this way, measurements of relaxation times can provide information of motions within a molecule on the atomic level.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] In NMR studies of protein dynamics, the nitrogen-15 isotope is the preferred nucleus to study because its relaxation times are relatively simple to relate to molecular motions.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] This, however, requires isotope labeling of the protein.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The T1 and T2 relaxation times can be measured using various types of HSQC-based experiments.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The types of motions that can be detected are motions that occur on a time-scale ranging from about 10 picoseconds to about 10 nanoseconds.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] In addition, slower motions, which take place on a time-scale ranging from about 10 microseconds to 100 milliseconds, can also be studied.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] However, since nitrogen atoms are found mainly in the backbone of a protein, the results mainly reflect the motions of the backbone, which is the most rigid part of a protein molecule.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Thus, the results obtained from nitrogen-15 relaxation measurements may not be representative of the whole protein.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Therefore, techniques utilising relaxation measurements of carbon-13 and deuterium have recently been developed, which enables systematic studies of motions of the amino acid side-chains in proteins.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] A challenging and special case of study regarding dynamics and flexibility of peptides and full-length proteins is represented by disordered structures.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Nowadays, it is an accepted concept that proteins can exhibit a more flexible behaviour known as disorder or lack of structure; however, it is possible to describe an ensemble of structures instead of a static picture representing a fully functional state of the protein.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Many advances are represented in this field in particular in terms of new pulse sequences, technological improvement, and rigorous training of researchers in the field.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Traditionally, nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy has been limited to relatively small proteins or protein domains.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] This is in part caused by problems resolving overlapping peaks in larger proteins, but this has been alleviated by the introduction of isotope labelling and multidimensional experiments.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Another more serious problem is the fact that in large proteins the magnetization relaxes faster, which means there is less time to detect the signal.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] This in turn causes the peaks to become broader and weaker, and eventually disappear.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Two techniques have been introduced to attenuate the relaxation: transverse relaxation optimized spectroscopy (TROSY) and deuteration of proteins.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] By using these techniques it has been possible to study proteins in complex with the 900 kDa chaperone GroES-GroEL.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Structure determination by NMR has traditionally been a time-consuming process, requiring interactive analysis of the data by a highly trained scientist.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] There has been considerable interest in automating the process to increase the throughput of structure determination and to make protein NMR accessible to non-experts (See structural genomics).
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] The two most time-consuming processes involved are the sequence-specific resonance assignment (backbone and side-chain assignment) and the NOE assignment tasks.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Several different computer programs have been published that target individual parts of the overall NMR structure determination process in an automated fashion.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Most progress has been achieved for the task of automated NOE assignment.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] So far, only the FLYA and the UNIO approach were proposed to perform the entire protein NMR structure determination process in an automated manner without any human intervention.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Modules in the NMRFAM-SPARKY such as APES (two-letter-code: ae), I-PINE/PINE-SPARKY (two-letter-code: ep; I-PINE web server) and PONDEROSA (two-letter-code: c3, up; PONDEROSA web server) are integrated so that it offers full automation with visual verification capability in each step.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Efforts have also been made to standardize the structure calculation protocol to make it quicker and more amenable to automation.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy-of-proteins] Recently, the POKY suite, the successor of programs mentioned above, has been released to provide modern GUI tools and AI/ML features.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The **nuclear Overhauser effect** (**NOE**) is the transfer of nuclear spin polarization from one population of spin-active nuclei (e.g.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] 1H, 13C, 15N etc.) to another via cross-relaxation.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] A phenomenological definition of the NOE in nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy (NMR) is the change in the integrated intensity (positive or negative) of one NMR resonance that occurs when another is saturated by irradiation with an RF field.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The change in resonance intensity of a nucleus is a consequence of the nucleus being close in space to those directly affected by the RF perturbation.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The NOE is particularly important in the assignment of NMR resonances, and the elucidation and confirmation of the structures or configurations of organic and biological molecules.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The 1H two-dimensional NOE spectroscopy (NOESY) experiment and its extensions are important tools to identify stereochemistry of proteins and other biomolecules in solution, whereas in solid form crystal x-ray diffraction typically used to identify stereochemistry.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The NOE developed from the theoretical work of American physicist Albert Overhauser who in 1953 proposed that *nuclear* spin polarization could be enhanced by the microwave irradiation of the conduction *electrons* in certain metals.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The electron-nuclear enhancement predicted by Overhauser was experimentally demonstrated in 7Li metal by T.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] A general theoretical basis and experimental observation of an Overhauser effect involving only *nuclear* spins in the HF molecule was published by Ionel Solomon in 1955.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Another early experimental observation of the NOE was used by Kaiser in 1963 to show how the NOE may be used to determine the relative signs of scalar coupling constants, and to assign spectral lines in NMR spectra to transitions between energy levels.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In this study, the resonance of one population of protons (1H) in an organic molecule was enhanced when a second distinct population of protons in the same organic molecule was saturated by RF irradiation.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The application of the NOE was used by Anet and Bourn in 1965 to confirm the assignments of the NMR resonances for β,β-dimethylacrylic acid and dimethyl formamide, thereby showing that conformation and configuration information about organic molecules in solution can be obtained.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Bell and Saunders reported direct correlation between NOE enhancements and internuclear distances in 1970 while quantitative measurements of internuclear distances in molecules with three or more spins was reported by Schirmer et al.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Ernst was awarded the 1991 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for developing Fourier transform and two-dimensional NMR spectroscopy, which was soon adapted to the measurement of the NOE, particularly in large biological molecules.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Professor Anil Kumar was the first to apply the two-dimensional Nuclear Overhauser Effect (2D-NOE now known as NOESY) experiment to a biomolecule, which opened the field for the determination of three-dimensional structures of biomolecules in solution by NMR spectroscopy.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The NOE and nuclear spin-lattice relaxation are closely related phenomena.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] For a single spin-1⁄2 nucleus in a magnetic field there are two energy levels that are often labeled α and β, which correspond to the two possible spin quantum states, +1⁄2 and -1⁄2, respectively.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] At thermal equilibrium, the population of the two energy levels is determined by the Boltzmann distribution with spin populations given by *P*α and *P*β.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] If the spin populations are perturbed by an appropriate RF field at the transition energy frequency, the spin populations return to thermal equilibrium by a process called *spin-lattice relaxation*.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The rate of transitions from α to β is proportional to the population of state α, *P*α, and is a first order process with rate constant *W*.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The condition where the spin populations are equalized by continuous RF irradiation (*P*α = *P*β) is called *saturation* and the resonance disappears since transition probabilities depend on the population difference between the energy levels.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In the simplest case where the NOE is relevant, the resonances of two spin-1⁄2 nuclei, I and S, are chemically shifted but not J-coupled.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The energy diagram for such a system has four energy levels that depend on the spin-states of I and S corresponding to αα, αβ, βα, and ββ, respectively.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The *W'*s are the probabilities per unit time that a transition will occur between the four energy levels, or in other terms the rate at which the corresponding spin flips occur.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] There are two single quantum transitions, *W*1I, corresponding to αα ➞ βα and αβ ➞ ββ; *W*1S, corresponding to αα ➞ αβ and βα ➞ ββ; a zero quantum transition, *W*0, corresponding to βα ➞ αβ, and a double quantum transition corresponding to αα ➞ ββ.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] While rf irradiation can only induce single-quantum transitions (due to so-called quantum mechanical selection rules) giving rise to observable spectral lines, dipolar relaxation may take place through any of the pathways.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The dipolar mechanism is the only common relaxation mechanism that can cause transitions in which more than one spin flips.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Specifically, the dipolar relaxation mechanism gives rise to transitions between the αα and ββ states (*W*2) and between the αβ and the βα states (*W*0).
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] where $M_{0I}$ is the magnetization (resonance intensity) of nucleus I at thermal equilibrium.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] $\rho _{I}$ is the total longitudinal dipolar relaxation rate ( $1/T_{1}$ ) of spin *I* due to the presence of spin *s*, $\sigma _{IS}$ is referred to as the *cross-relaxation* rate, and $\gamma _{I}$ and $\gamma _{S}$ are the magnetogyric ratios characteristic of the I and S nuclei, respectively.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Saturation of the degenerate *W*1S transitions disturbs the equilibrium populations so that *P*αα = *P*αβ and *P*βα = *P*ββ.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] This means that if only the single quantum transitions were active as relaxation pathways, saturating the S resonance would not affect the intensity of the I resonance.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Therefore to observe an NOE on the resonance intensity of I, the contribution of $W_{0}$ and $W_{2}$ must be important.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] These pathways, known as *cross-relaxation* pathways, only make a significant contribution to the spin-lattice relaxation when the relaxation is dominated by dipole-dipole or scalar coupling interactions, but the scalar interaction is rarely important and is assumed to be negligible.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Whether the NOE is positive or negative depends sensitively on the degree of rotational molecular motion.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The three dipolar relaxation pathways contribute to differing extents to the spin-lattice relaxation depending a number of factors.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] A key one is that the balance between ω2, ω1 and ω0 depends crucially on molecular rotational correlation time, $\tau _{c}$ , the time it takes a molecule to rotate one radian.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] where r is the distance separating two spin-1⁄2 nuclei.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] For relaxation to occur, the frequency of molecular tumbling must match the Larmor frequency of the nucleus.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In mobile solvents, molecular tumbling motion is much faster than $\omega$ .
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The so-called extreme-narrowing limit where $\omega \tau _{c}\ll 1$ ).
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Under these conditions the double-quantum relaxation W2 is more effective than W1 or W0, because τc and 2ω0 match better than τc and ω1.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] When ω2 is the dominant relaxation process, a positive NOE results.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] This expression shows that for the homonuclear case where *I* = *S*, most notably for 1*H* NMR, the maximum NOE that can be observed is 1\2 irrespective of the proximity of the nuclei.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In the heteronuclear case where *I* ≠ *S*, the maximum NOE is given by 1\2 (*γ*S/*γ*I), which, when observing heteronuclei under conditions of broadband proton decoupling, can produce major sensitivity improvements.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The most important example in organic chemistry is observation of 13C while decoupling 1H, which also saturates the 1J resonances.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The value of *γ*S/*γ*I is close to 4, which gives a maximum NOE enhancement of 200% yielding resonances 3 times as strong as they would be without NOE.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In many cases, carbon atoms have an attached proton, which causes the relaxation to be dominated by dipolar relaxation and the NOE to be near maximum.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] For non-protonated carbon atoms the NOE enhancement is small while for carbons that relax by relaxation mechanisms by other than dipole-dipole interactions the NOE enhancement can be significantly reduced.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] This is one motivation for using deuteriated solvents (e.g.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Since deuterium relaxes by the quadrupolar mechanism, there are no cross-relaxation pathways and NOE is non-existent.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Another important case is 15N, an example where the value of its magnetogyric ratio is negative.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Often 15N resonances are reduced or the NOE may actually null out the resonance when 1H nuclei are decoupled.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] It is usually advantageous to take such spectra with pulse techniques that involve polarization transfer from protons to the 15N to minimize the negative NOE.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] For example, NOE enhancements can be used to confirm NMR resonance assignments, distinguish between structural isomers, identify aromatic ring substitution patterns and aliphatic substituent configurations, and determine conformational preferences.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The inter-atomic distances derived from the observed NOE can often help to confirm the three-dimensional structure of a molecule.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In this application, the NOE differs from the application of J-coupling in that the NOE occurs through space, not through chemical bonds.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Thus, atoms that are in close spatial proximity to each other can give an NOE regardless of how many chemical bonds separate them, whereas spin coupling is observed only when the atoms are connected by 1–3 chemical bonds.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] However, the relation *η*IS(max)=1⁄2 obscures how the NOE is related to internuclear distances because it applies only for the idealized case where the relaxation is 100% dominated by dipole-dipole interactions between two nuclei I and S.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In practice, the value of ρI contains contributions from other competing mechanisms, which serve only to reduce the influence of *W*0 and *W*2 by increasing *W*1.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Sometimes, for example, relaxation due to electron-nuclear interactions with dissolved oxygen or paramagnetic metal ion impurities in the solvent can prohibit the observation of weak NOE enhancements.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] where ρ⋇ is the additional contribution to the total relaxation rate from relaxation mechanisms not involving cross relaxation.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Thus, the two-spin steady-state NOE depends on internuclear distance only when there is a contribution from external relaxation.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Bell and Saunders showed that following strict assumptions ρ⋇/τc is nearly constant for similar molecules in the extreme narrowing limit.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Therefore, taking ratios of steady-state NOE values can give relative values for the internuclear distance *r*.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] While the steady-state experiment is useful in many cases, it can only provide information on relative internuclear distances.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] On the other hand, the initial *rate* at which the NOE grows is proportional to *r*IS−6, which provides other more sophisticated alternatives for obtaining structural information via transient experiments such as 2D-NOESY.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The motivations for using two-dimensional NMR for measuring NOEs are similar as for other 2-D methods.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The maximum resolution is improved by spreading the affected resonances over two dimensions, therefore more peaks are resolved, larger molecules can be observed and more NOEs can be observed in a single measurement.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] More importantly, when the molecular motion is in the intermediate or slow motional regimes when the NOE is either zero or negative, the steady-state NOE experiment fails to give results that can be related to internuclear distances.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Nuclear Overhauser Effect Spectroscopy (NOESY) is a 2D NMR spectroscopic method used to identify nuclear spins undergoing cross-relaxation and to measure their cross-relaxation rates.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Since 1H dipole-dipole couplings provide the primary means of cross-relaxation for organic molecules in solution, spins undergoing cross-relaxation are those close to one another in space.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Therefore, the cross peaks of a NOESY spectrum indicate which protons are close to each other in space.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In this respect, the NOESY experiment differs from the COSY experiment that relies on J-coupling to provide spin-spin correlation, and whose cross peaks indicate which 1H's are close to which other 1H's through the chemical bonds of the molecule.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The basic NOESY sequence consists of three 90° pulses.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The first pulse creates transverse spin magnetization.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The spins precess during the evolution time t1, which is incremented during the course of the 2D experiment.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The second pulse produces longitudinal magnetization equal to the transverse magnetization component orthogonal to the pulse direction.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Thus, the idea is to produce an initial condition for the mixing period τm.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] During the NOE mixing time, magnetization transfer via cross-relaxation can take place.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] For the basic NOESY experiment, τm is kept constant throughout the 2D experiment, but chosen for the optimum cross-relaxation rate and build-up of the NOE.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The third pulse creates transverse magnetization from the remaining longitudinal magnetization.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Data acquisition begins immediately following the third pulse and the transverse magnetization is observed as a function of the pulse delay time t2.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The NOESY spectrum is generated by a 2D Fourier transform with respect to t1 and t2.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] A series of experiments are carried out with increasing mixing times, and the increase in NOE enhancement is followed.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The closest protons show the most rapid build-up rates of the NOE.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Inter-proton distances can be determined from unambiguously assigned, well-resolved, high signal-to-noise NOESY spectra by analysis of cross peak intensities.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] These may be obtained by volume integration and can be converted into estimates of interproton distances.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] where c can be determined based on measurements of known fixed distances.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The range of distances can be reported based on known distances and volumes in the spectrum, which gives a mean c and a standard deviation $c_{SD}$ , a measurement of multiple regions in the NOESY spectrum showing no peaks, *i.e.* noise $V_{\rm {err}}$ , and a measurement error $m_{v}$ .
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The parameter x is set so that all known distances are within the error bounds.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Such fixed distances depend on the system studied.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] For example, locked nucleic acids have many atoms whose distance varies very little in the sugar, which allows estimation of the glycosidic torsion angles, which allowed NMR to benchmark LNA molecular dynamics predictions.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] RNAs, however, have sugars that are much more conformationally flexible, and require wider estimations of low and high bounds.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In protein structural characterization, NOEs are used to create constraints on intramolecular distances.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In this method, each proton pair is considered in isolation and NOESY cross peak intensities are compared with a reference cross peak from a proton pair of fixed distance, such as a geminal methylene proton pair or aromatic ring protons.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] This simple approach is reasonably insensitive to the effects of spin diffusion or non-uniform correlation times and can usually lead to definition of the global fold of the protein, provided a sufficiently large number of NOEs have been identified.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] NOESY cross peaks can be classified as strong, medium or weak and can be translated into upper distance restraints of around 2.5, 3.5 and 5.0 Å, respectively.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Such constraints can then be used in molecular mechanics optimizations to provide a picture of the solution state conformation of the protein.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Full structure determination relies on a variety of NMR experiments and optimization methods utilizing both chemical shift and NOESY constraints.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] NOESY is the determination of the relative orientations of atoms in a molecule, for example a protein or other large biological molecule, producing a three-dimensional structure.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] HOESY is NOESY cross-correlation between atoms of different elements.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] ROESY involves spin-locking the magnetization to prevent it from going to zero, applied for molecules for which regular NOESY is not applicable.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] TRNOE measures the NOE between two different molecules interacting in the same solution, as in a ligand binding to a protein.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In a DPFGSE-NOE experiment, a transient experiment that allows for suppression of strong signals and thus detection of very small NOEs.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] The figure (top) displays how Nuclear Overhauser Effect Spectroscopy can elucidate the structure of a switchable compound.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In this example, the proton designated as {H} shows two different sets of NOEs depending on the isomerization state (*cis* or *trans*) of the switchable azo groups.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] In the *trans* state proton {H} is far from the phenyl group showing blue coloured NOEs; while the *cis* state holds proton {H} in the vicinity of the phenyl group resulting in the emergence of new NOEs (show in red).
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Another example (bottom) where application where the NOE is useful to assign resonances and determine configuration is polysaccharides.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] For instance, complex glucans possess a multitude of overlapping signals, especially in a proton spectrum.
[src:protein-nmr/nuclear-overhauser-effect] Therefore, it is advantageous to utilize 2D NMR experiments including NOESY for the assignment of signals.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] In molecular biology, proteins are generally thought to adopt unique structures determined by their amino acid sequences.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] However, proteins are not strictly static objects, but rather populate ensembles of (sometimes similar) conformations.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Transitions between these states occur on a variety of length scales (tenths of angstroms to nm) and time scales (ns to s), and have been linked to functionally relevant phenomena such as allosteric signaling and enzyme catalysis.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] The study of **protein dynamics** is most directly concerned with the transitions between these states, but can also involve the nature and equilibrium populations of the states themselves.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] These two perspectives—kinetics and thermodynamics, respectively—can be conceptually synthesized in an "energy landscape" paradigm: highly populated states and the kinetics of transitions between them can be described by the depths of energy wells and the heights of energy barriers, respectively.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Portions of protein structures often deviate from the equilibrium state.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Some such excursions are harmonic, such as stochastic fluctuations of chemical bonds and bond angles.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Others are anharmonic, such as sidechains that jump between separate discrete energy minima, or rotamers.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Evidence for local flexibility is often obtained from NMR spectroscopy.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Flexible and potentially disordered regions of a protein can be detected using the random coil index.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Flexibility in folded proteins can be identified by analyzing the spin relaxation of individual atoms in the protein.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Flexibility can also be observed in very high-resolution electron density maps produced by X-ray crystallography, particularly when diffraction data is collected at room temperature instead of the traditional cryogenic temperature (typically near 100 K).
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Information on the frequency distribution and dynamics of local protein flexibility can be obtained using Raman and optical Kerr-effect spectroscopy as well as anisotropic microspectroscopy in the terahertz frequency domain.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] The internal re-arrangement of the amino acids during protein motion involves elastic and plastic deformations induced by viscoelastic forces, which can be probed with nano-rheology techniques.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Many residues are in close spatial proximity in protein structures.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] This is true for most residues that are contiguous in the primary sequence, but also for many that are distal in sequence yet are brought into contact in the final folded structure.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Because of this proximity, these residues' energy landscapes become coupled based on various biophysical phenomena such as hydrogen bonds, ionic bonds, and van der Waals interactions (see figure).
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Transitions between states for such sets of residues therefore become correlated.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] This is perhaps most obvious for surface-exposed loops, which often shift collectively to adopt different conformations in different crystal structures.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] However, coupled conformational heterogeneity is also sometimes evident in secondary structure.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] For example, consecutive residues and residues offset by 4 in the primary sequence often interact in α helices.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Also, residues offset by 2 in the primary sequence point their sidechains toward the same face of β sheets and are close enough to interact sterically, as are residues on adjacent strands of the same β sheet.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Some of these conformational changes are induced by post-translational modifications in protein structure, such as phosphorylation and methylation.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] When these coupled residues form pathways linking functionally important parts of a protein, they may participate in allosteric signaling.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] For example, when a molecule of oxygen binds to one subunit of the hemoglobin tetramer, that information is allosterically propagated to the other three subunits, thereby enhancing their affinity for oxygen.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] In this case, the coupled flexibility in hemoglobin allows for cooperative oxygen binding, which is physiologically useful because it allows rapid oxygen loading in lung tissue and rapid oxygen unloading in oxygen-deprived tissues (e.g. muscle).
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] The presence of multiple domains in proteins gives rise to a great deal of flexibility and mobility, leading to **protein domain dynamics**.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Domain motions can be directly observed using spectra measured by neutron spin echo spectroscopy.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] They can also be suggested by sampling in extensive molecular dynamics trajectories and principal component analysis or inferred by comparing different structures of a protein (as in Database of Molecular Motions).
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] One of the largest observed domain motions is the 'swivelling' mechanism in pyruvate phosphate dikinase.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] The phosphoinositide domain swivels between two states in order to bring a phosphate group from the active site of the nucleotide binding domain to that of the phosphoenolpyruvate/pyruvate domain.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] The phosphate group is moved over a distance of 45 Å involving a domain motion of about 100 degrees around a single residue.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] In enzymes, the closure of one domain onto another captures a substrate by an induced fit, allowing the reaction to take place in a controlled way.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] A detailed analysis by Gerstein led to the classification of two basic types of domain motion; hinge and shear.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Only a relatively small portion of the chain, namely the inter-domain linker and side chains undergo significant conformational changes upon domain rearrangement.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] A study by Hayward found that the termini of α-helices and β-sheets form hinges in a large number of cases.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Many hinges were found to involve two secondary structure elements acting like hinges of a door, allowing an opening and closing motion to occur.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] This can arise when two neighbouring strands within a β-sheet situated in one domain, diverge apart as they join the other domain.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] The two resulting termini then form the bending regions between the two domains. α-helices that preserve their hydrogen bonding network when bent are found to behave as mechanical hinges, storing `elastic energy' that drives the closure of domains for rapid capture of a substrate.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Khade et. al. worked on prediction of the hinges in any conformation and further built an Elastic Network Model called hdANM that can model those motions.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] The interconversion of helical and extended conformations at the site of a domain boundary is not uncommon.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] In calmodulin, torsion angles change for five residues in the middle of a domain linking α-helix.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] The helix is split into two, almost perpendicular, smaller helices separated by four residues of an extended strand.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Shear motions involve a small sliding movement of domain interfaces, controlled by the amino acid side chains within the interface.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Proteins displaying shear motions often have a layered architecture: stacking of secondary structures.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] The interdomain linker has merely the role of keeping the domains in close proximity.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] The analysis of the internal dynamics of structurally different, but functionally similar enzymes has highlighted a common relationship between the positioning of the active site and the two principal protein sub-domains.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] In fact, for several members of the hydrolase superfamily, the catalytic site is located close to the interface separating the two principal quasi-rigid domains.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Such positioning appears instrumental for maintaining the precise geometry of the active site, while allowing for an appreciable functionally oriented modulation of the flanking regions resulting from the relative motion of the two sub-domains.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] A natural measure to quantify and classify the subtle motions of amino acids that occur during conformational changes is the strain.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] When a group of amino acids moves together as a rigid body, the strain vanishes.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] In contrast, high strain values indicate that neighboring amino acids and atoms have moved with respect to each other.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] The effective strain is the relative change in distances between neighboring amino acids, which is a sensitive enough measure to probe the effects of single mutations on the structural landscape of protein.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Evidence suggests that protein dynamics are important for function, e.g. enzyme catalysis in dihydrofolate reductase (DHFR), yet they are also posited to facilitate the acquisition of new functions by molecular evolution.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] This argument suggests that proteins have evolved to have stable, mostly unique folded structures, but the unavoidable residual flexibility leads to some degree of functional promiscuity, which can be amplified/harnessed/diverted by subsequent mutations.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] Research on promiscuous proteins within the BCL-2 family revealed that nanosecond-scale protein dynamics can play a crucial role in protein binding behaviour and thus promiscuity.
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] However, there is growing awareness that intrinsically unstructured proteins are quite prevalent in eukaryotic genomes, casting further doubt on the simplest interpretation of Anfinsen's dogma: "sequence determines structure (singular)".
[src:protein-nmr/protein-dynamics] In effect, the new paradigm is characterized by the addition of two caveats: "sequence and cellular environment determine structural ensemble".
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] The **residual dipolar coupling** between two spins in a molecule occurs if the molecules in solution exhibit a partial alignment leading to an incomplete averaging of spatially anisotropic dipolar couplings.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] Partial molecular alignment leads to an incomplete averaging of anisotropic magnetic interactions such as the magnetic dipole-dipole interaction (also called dipolar coupling), the chemical shift anisotropy, or the electric quadrupole interaction.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] The resulting so-called *residual* anisotropic magnetic interactions are useful in biomolecular NMR spectroscopy.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] NMR spectroscopy in partially oriented media was reported by Alfred Saupe.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] After this initiation, several NMR spectra in various liquid crystalline phases were reported (see *e.g.* ).
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] A second technique for partial alignment that is not limited by a minimum anisotropy is strain-induced alignment in a gel (SAG).
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] The technique was extensively used to study the properties of polymer gels by means of high-resolution deuterium NMR, but only lately gel alignment was used to induce RDCs in molecules dissolved into the gel.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] SAG allows the unrestricted scaling of alignment over a wide range and can be used for aqueous as well as organic solvents, depending on the polymer used.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] As a first example in organic solvents, RDC measurements in stretched polystyrene (PS) gels swollen in CDCl3 were reported as a promising alignment method.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] In 1995, NMR spectra were reported for cyanometmyoglobin, which has a very highly anisotropic paramagnetic susceptibility.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] When taken at very high field, these spectra may contain data that can usefully complement NOEs in determining a tertiary fold.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] In 1996 and 1997, the RDCs of a diamagnetic protein ubiquitin were reported.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] The results were in good agreement with the crystal structures.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] In isotropic solution molecular tumbling reduces the average value of $D_{IS}$ to zero.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] If the solution is not isotropic then the average value of $D_{IS}$ may be different from zero, and one may observe *residual* couplings.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] The positions of magnetic nuclei are often relatively restricted in solid sample, so there are a large number of dipolar coupling dominating in different nuclei.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] The static value of dipole coupling may reach thousands of hertz, which will cause serious broadening of the spectral peaks in the solid-state NMR spectra.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] In liquid samples, due to isotropic tumbling of the molecule, the dipole coupling effect is averaged to zero.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] Although high-resolution spectra can be thus obtained in the solution, structural information provided by dipolar coupling becomes lost.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] When compound molecules are placed in a weakly oriented medium, the movement of the molecules is partially restricted.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] Compared with the solid sample, the static value of the dipole coupling is reduced by around 103 times.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] Compared with the liquid sample, the dipole coupling effect is not completely averaged, and it retains a smaller residual value, that is residual dipolar coupling (RDC).
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] RDC can be positive or negative, depending on the range of angles that are sampled.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] In addition to static distance and angular information, RDCs may contain information about a molecule's internal motion.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] where A is the molecular alignment tensor.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] The rows of B contain the motion tensors for each atom.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] The motion tensors also have five degrees of freedom.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] From each motion tensor, 5 parameters of interest can be computed.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] The variables Si2, ηi, αi, βi and γi are used to denote these 5 parameters for atom i.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] Si2 is the magnitude of atom i's motion; ηi is a measure of the anisotropy of atom i's motion; αi and βi are related to the polar coordinates of the bond vector expressed in the initial arbitrary reference frame (i.e., the PDB frame).
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] If the motion of the atom is anisotropic (i.e., ηi = 0), the final parameter, γi measures the principal orientation of the motion.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] Note that the RDC-derived motion parameters are local measurements.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] For diamagnetic molecules at moderate field strengths, molecules have little preference in orientation, the tumbling samples a nearly isotropic distribution, and average dipolar couplings goes to zero.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] Actually, most molecules have preferred orientations in the presence of a magnetic field, because most have anisotropic magnetic susceptibility tensors, Χ.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] The method is most suitable for systems with large values for magnetic susceptibility tensor.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] This includes: Protein-nucleic acid complex, nucleic acids, proteins with large number of aromatic residues, porphyrin containing proteins and metal binding proteins (metal may be replaced by lanthanides).
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] For a fully oriented molecule, the dipolar coupling for an 1H-15N amide group would be over 20 kHz, and a pair of protons separated by 5 Å would have up to ~1 kHz coupling.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] However the degree of alignment achieved by applying magnetic field is so low that the largest 1H-15N or 1H-13C dipolar couplings are <5 Hz.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] There are numerous methods that have been designed to accurately measure coupling constant between nuclei.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] They have been classified into two groups: *frequency based methods* where separation of peaks centers (splitting) is measured in a frequency domain, and *intensity based methods* where the coupling is extracted from the resonance intensity instead of splitting.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] The two methods complement each other as each of them is subject to a different kind of systematic errors.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] RDC measurement provides information on the global folding of the protein or protein complex.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] As opposed to traditional NOE based NMR structure determinations, RDCs provide long distance structural information.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] It also provides information about the dynamics in molecules on time scales slower than nanoseconds.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] Most NMR studies of protein structure are based on analysis of the Nuclear Overhauser effect, NOE, between different protons in the protein.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] Because the NOE depends on the inverted sixth power of the distance between the nuclei, r−6, NOEs can be converted into distance restraints that can be used in molecular dynamics-type structure calculations.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] Provided that a very complete set of RDCs is available, it has been demonstrated for several model systems that molecular structures can be calculated exclusively based on these anisotropic interactions, without recourse to NOE restraints.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] However, in practice, this is not achievable and RDC is used mainly to refine a structure determined by NOE data and J-coupling.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] One problem with using dipolar couplings in structure determination is that a dipolar coupling does not uniquely describe an internuclear vector orientation.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] Moreover, if a very small set of dipolar couplings are available, the refinement may lead to a structure worse than the original one.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] For a protein with N aminoacids, 2N RDC constraint for backbone is the minimum needed for an accurate refinement.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] Such a curve (see figure) has two symmetrical branches that lie on a sphere with its polar axis along the magnetic field direction.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] Their height from the sphere's equator depends on the magnitude of the RDC value and their shape depends on the "rhombicity" (asymmetry) of the molecular alignment tensor.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] If the molecular alignment were completely symmetrical around the magnetic field direction, the target curve would just consist of two circles at the same angle from the poles as the angle $\theta$ that the specific bond vector makes to the applied magnetic field.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] Particularly, RNA molecules are proton-poor and overlap of ribose resonances make it very difficult to use J-coupling and NOE data to determine the structure.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] Moreover, RDCs between nuclei with a distance larger than 5-6 Å can be detected.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] This distance is too much for generation of NOE signal.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] This is because RDC is proportional to r−3 whereas NOE is proportional to r−6.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] RDC measurements have also been proved to be extremely useful for a rapid determination of the relative orientations of units of known structures in proteins.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] In principle, the orientation of a structural subunit, which may be as small as a turn of a helix or as large as an entire domain, can be established from as few as five RDCs per subunit.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] As a RDC provides spatially and temporally averaged information about an angle between the external magnetic field and a bond vector in a molecule, it may provide rich geometrical information about dynamics on a slow timescale (>10−9 s) in proteins.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] However, for many classes of proteins, including intrinsically disordered proteins, analysis of RDCs becomes more involved, as defining an alignment frame is not trivial.
[src:protein-nmr/residual-dipolar-coupling] The problem can be addressed by circumventing the necessity of explicitly defining the alignment frame.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] 2D NMR encompasses a variety of experiments, including **COSY** (Correlation Spectroscopy), **TOCSY** (Total Correlation Spectroscopy), **NOESY** (Nuclear Overhauser Effect Spectroscopy), and **HSQC** (Heteronuclear Single Quantum Coherence).
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] By resolving signals that would typically overlap in the 1D NMR spectra of complex molecules, 2D NMR enhances the clarity of structural information.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] 2D NMR can provide detailed information about the chemical structure and the three-dimensional arrangement of molecules.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The first two-dimensional experiment, COSY, was proposed by Jean Jeener, a professor at the Université Libre de Bruxelles, in 1971.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This experiment was later implemented by Walter P.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Ernst, who published their work in 1976.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Each experiment consists of a sequence of radio frequency (RF) pulses with delay periods in between them.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The timing, frequencies, and intensities of these pulses distinguish different NMR experiments from one another.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The two dimensions of a two-dimensional NMR experiment are two frequency axes representing a chemical shift.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Each frequency axis is associated with one of the two time variables, which are the length of the evolution period (the *evolution time*) and the time elapsed during the detection period (the *detection time*).
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] They are each converted from a time series to a frequency series through a two-dimensional Fourier transform, one in the time domain and based on the signals from each different t1 experiment.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] A single two-dimensional experiment is generated as a series of one-dimensional experiments, with a different specific evolution time in successive experiments, with the entire duration of the detection period recorded in each experiment.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The end result is a plot showing an intensity value for each pair of frequency variables.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The intensities of the peaks in the spectrum can be represented using a third dimension.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] More commonly, intensity is indicated using contour lines or different colors.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In these methods, magnetization transfer occurs between nuclei of the same type, through J-coupling of nuclei connected by up to a few bonds.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The first and most popular two-dimension NMR experiment is the homonuclear correlation spectroscopy (COSY) sequence, which is used to identify spins which are coupled to each other.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] It consists of a single RF pulse (p1) followed by the specific evolution time (t1) followed by a second pulse (p2) followed by a measurement period (t2).
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The Correlation Spectroscopy experiment operates by correlating nuclei coupled to each other through scalar coupling, also known as J-coupling.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This coupling is the interaction between nuclear spins connected by bonds, typically observed between nuclei that are 2-3 bonds apart (e.g., vicinal protons).
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] By detecting these interactions, COSY provides vital information about the connectivity between atoms within a molecule, making it a crucial tool for structural elucidation in organic chemistry.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The COSY experiment generates a two-dimensional spectrum with chemical shifts along the x-axis (horizontal) and y-axis (vertical) and involves several key steps.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] First, the sample is excited using a series of radiofrequency (RF) pulses, bringing the nuclear spins into a higher energy state.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] After the first RF pulse, the system evolves freely for a period called t1, during which the spins precess at frequencies corresponding to their chemical shifts.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The correlation between nuclei is achieved by incrementally varying the evolution time (t1) to capture indirect interactions.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This series of experiments, each with a different value of t1, allows for the detection of chemical shifts from nuclei that may not be observed directly in a one-dimensional spectrum.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] As t1 is incremented, cross-peaks are produced in the resulting 2D spectrum, representing interactions like coupling or spatial proximity between nuclei.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This approach helps map out atomic connections, providing deeper insight into molecular structure and aiding in the interpretation of complex systems.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Cross peaks result from a phenomenon called magnetization transfer, and their presence indicates that two nuclei are coupled which have the two different chemical shifts that make up the cross peak's coordinates.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Each coupling gives two symmetrical cross peaks above and below the diagonal.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] That is, a cross-peak occurs when there is a correlation between the signals of the spectrum along each of the two axes at these values.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] An easy visual way to determine which couplings a cross peak represents is to find the diagonal peak which is directly above or below the cross peak, and the other diagonal peak which is directly to the left or right of the cross peak.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The nuclei represented by those two diagonal peaks are coupled.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Next, a second RF pulse is applied to allow magnetization to transfer between coupled nuclei.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The resulting signal is recorded continuously during a detection period ( t2) after the second RF pulse.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The data are then processed through Fourier transformation along both the t1 and t2 axes, creating a 2D spectrum with peaks plotted along the diagonal and off-diagonal.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] When interpreting the COSY spectrum, diagonal peaks correspond to the 1D chemical shifts of individual nuclei, similar to the standard peaks in a 1D NMR spectrum.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The key feature of a COSY spectrum is the presence of cross-peaks as shown in Figure 1, indicating coupling between pairs of nuclei.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] These cross-peaks provide crucial information about the connectivity within a molecule, showing that the two nuclei are connected by a small number of bonds, usually two or three bonds.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] COSY is especially useful when dealing with complex molecules such as natural products, peptides, and proteins, where understanding the connectivity of different nuclei through bonds is crucial.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] While 1D NMR is more straightforward and ideal for identifying basic structural features, COSY enhances the capabilities of NMR by providing deeper insights into molecular connectivity.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The two-dimensional spectrum that results from the COSY experiment shows the frequencies for a single isotope, most commonly hydrogen (1H) along both axes.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] COSY-90 is the most common COSY experiment.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In COSY-90, the p1 pulse tilts the nuclear spin by 90°.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Another member of the COSY family is **COSY-45**.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In COSY-45 a 45° pulse is used instead of a 90° pulse for the second pulse, p2.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The advantage of a COSY-45 is that the diagonal-peaks are less pronounced, making it simpler to match cross-peaks near the diagonal in a large molecule.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Additionally, the relative signs of the coupling constants (see J-coupling#Magnitude of J-coupling) can be elucidated from a COSY-45 spectrum.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Overall, the COSY-45 offers a cleaner spectrum while the COSY-90 is more sensitive.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Another related COSY technique is double quantum filtered (DQF) COSY.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] DQF COSY uses a coherence selection method such as phase cycling or pulsed field gradients, which cause only signals from double-quantum coherences to give an observable signal.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This has the effect of decreasing the intensity of the diagonal peaks and changing their lineshape from a broad "dispersion" lineshape to a sharper "absorption" lineshape.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] It also eliminates diagonal peaks from uncoupled nuclei.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] These all have the advantage that they give a cleaner spectrum in which the diagonal peaks are prevented from obscuring the cross peaks, which are weaker in a regular COSY spectrum.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The TOCSY experiment is similar to the COSY experiment, in that cross peaks of coupled protons are observed.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] However, cross peaks are observed not only for nuclei which are directly coupled, but also between nuclei which are connected by a chain of couplings.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This makes it useful for identifying the larger interconnected networks of spin couplings.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This ability is achieved by inserting a repetitive series of pulses which cause *isotropic mixing* during the mixing period.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Longer isotropic mixing times cause the polarization to spread out through an increasing number of bonds.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In the case of oligosaccharides, each sugar residue is an isolated spin system, so it is possible to differentiate all the protons of a specific sugar residue.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] A 1D version of TOCSY is also available, and by irradiating a single proton the rest of the spin system can be revealed.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Recent advances in this technique include the 1D-CSSF (chemical shift selective filter) TOCSY experiment, which produces higher quality spectra and allows coupling constants to be reliably extracted and used to help determine stereochemistry.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] TOCSY is sometimes called "homonuclear Hartmann–Hahn spectroscopy" (HOHAHA).
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] INADEQUATE is a method often used to find 13C couplings between adjacent carbon atoms.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Because the natural abundance of 13C is only about 1%, only about 0.01% of molecules being studied will have the two nearby 13C atoms needed for a signal in this experiment.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] However, correlation selection methods are used (similarly to DQF COSY) to prevent signals from single 13C atoms, so that the double 13C signals can be easily resolved.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Each coupled pair of nuclei gives a pair of peaks on the INADEQUATE spectrum which both have the same vertical coordinate, which is the sum of the chemical shifts of the nuclei; the horizontal coordinate of each peak is the chemical shift for each of the nuclei separately.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Heteronuclear correlation spectroscopy gives signal based upon coupling between nuclei of two different types.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Often the two nuclei are protons and another nucleus (called a "heteronucleus").
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For historical reasons, experiments which record the proton rather than the heteronucleus spectrum during the detection period are called "inverse" experiments.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This is because the low natural abundance of most heteronuclei would result in the proton spectrum being overwhelmed with signals from molecules with no active heteronuclei, making it useless for observing the desired, coupled signals.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] With the advent of techniques for suppressing these undesired signals, inverse correlation experiments such as HSQC, HMQC, and HMBC are actually much more common today.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] "Normal" heteronuclear correlation spectroscopy, in which the heteronucleus spectrum is recorded, is known as HETCOR.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Heteronuclear Single Quantum Coherence (HSQC) is a 2D NMR technique utilized for the detection of interactions between different types of nuclei which are separated by one bond, particularly a proton (1H) and a heteronucleus such as carbon (13C) or nitrogen (15N).
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This method gives one peak per pair of coupled nuclei, whose two coordinates are the chemical shifts of the two coupled atoms.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This method plays a role in structural elucidation, particularly in analyzing organic compounds, natural products, and biomolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] HSQC is designed to detect one-bond correlations between protons and heteronuclear atoms, providing insight into the connectivity of hydrogen and heteronuclear atoms through the transfer of magnetization.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The HSQC experiment involves a series of steps to generate a two-dimensional NMR spectrum.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Initially, the sample is excited using radiofrequency (RF) pulses, bringing the nuclear spins into an excited state and preparing them for magnetization transfer.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Magnetization is then transferred from the proton to the heteronucleus through a one-bond scalar coupling (J-coupling), ensuring that only directly bonded nuclei participate in the transfer.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Subsequently, the system evolves during a period called t1, and the magnetization is transferred back from the heteronuclear to the proton.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The final signal is detected, encoding both the proton and the heteronuclear information, and a Fourier transformation is performed to create a 2D spectrum correlating the proton and heteronuclear chemical shifts.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] HSQC works by transferring magnetization from the *I* nucleus (usually the proton) to the *S* nucleus (usually the heteroatom) using the INEPT pulse sequence; this first step is done because the proton has a greater equilibrium magnetization and thus this step creates a stronger signal.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The magnetization then evolves and then is transferred back to the *I* nucleus for observation.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] An extra spin echo step can then optionally be used to decouple the signal, simplifying the spectrum by collapsing multiplets to a single peak.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The undesired uncoupled signals are removed by running the experiment twice with the phase of one specific pulse reversed; this reverses the signs of the desired but not the undesired peaks, so subtracting the two spectra will give only the desired peaks.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Interpretation of the HSQC spectrum is based on the observation of cross-peaks, which indicates the direct bonding between protons and carbons or nitrogens.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Heteronuclear multiple-quantum correlation spectroscopy (HMQC) gives an identical spectrum as HSQC, but using a different method.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The two methods give similar quality results for small to medium-sized molecules, but HSQC is considered to be superior for larger molecules.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] HMBC detects heteronuclear correlations over longer ranges of about 2–4 bonds.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The difficulty of detecting multiple-bond correlations is that the HSQC and HMQC sequences contain a specific delay time between pulses which allows detection only of a range around a specific coupling constant.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This is not a problem for the single-bond methods since the coupling constants tend to lie in a narrow range, but multiple-bond coupling constants cover a much wider range and cannot all be captured in a single HSQC or HMQC experiment.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In HMBC, this difficulty is overcome by omitting one of these delays from an HMQC sequence.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This increases the range of coupling constants that can be detected, and also reduces signal loss from relaxation.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The cost is that this eliminates the possibility of decoupling the spectrum, and introduces phase distortions into the signal.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] There is a modification of the HMBC method which suppresses one-bond signals, leaving only the multiple-bond signals.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] These methods establish correlations between nuclei which are physically close to each other regardless of whether there is a bond between them.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] They use the nuclear Overhauser effect (NOE) by which nearby atoms (within about 5 Å) undergo cross relaxation by a mechanism related to spin–lattice relaxation.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In NOESY, the nuclear Overhauser cross relaxation between nuclear spins during the mixing period is used to establish the correlations.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The spectrum obtained is similar to COSY, with diagonal peaks and cross peaks, however the cross peaks connect resonances from nuclei that are spatially close rather than those that are through-bond coupled to each other.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NOESY spectra also contain extra *axial peaks* which do not provide extra information and can be eliminated through a different experiment by reversing the phase of the first pulse.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] One application of NOESY is in the study of large biomolecules, such as in protein NMR, in which relationships can often be assigned using sequential walking.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The NOESY experiment can also be performed in a one-dimensional fashion by pre-selecting individual resonances.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The spectra are read with the pre-selected nuclei giving a large, negative signal while neighboring nuclei are identified by weaker, positive signals.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This only reveals which peaks have measurable NOEs to the resonance of interest but takes much less time than the full 2D experiment.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In addition, if a pre-selected nucleus changes environment within the time scale of the experiment, multiple negative signals may be observed.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] This offers exchange information similar to the EXSY (exchange spectroscopy) NMR method.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] NOESY experiments are important tool to identify stereochemistry of a molecule in solvent whereas single crystal XRD used to identify stereochemistry of a molecule in solid form.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In HOESY, much like NOESY is used for the cross relaxation between nuclear spins.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] However, HOESY can offer information about other NMR active nuclei in a spatially relevant manner.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] The experiments typically observe NOEs from protons on X, X{1H}, but do not have to include protons.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] ROESY is similar to NOESY, except that the initial state is different.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Instead of observing cross relaxation from an initial state of *z*-magnetization, the equilibrium magnetization is rotated onto the *x* axis and then spin-locked by an external magnetic field so that it cannot precess.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] In NOESY the cross-relaxation rate constant goes from positive to negative as the correlation time increases, giving a range where it is near zero, whereas in ROESY the cross-relaxation rate constant is always positive.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] ROESY is sometimes called "cross relaxation appropriate for minimolecules emulated by locked spins" (CAMELSPIN).
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Unlike correlated spectra, resolved spectra spread the peaks in a 1D-NMR experiment into two dimensions without adding any extra peaks.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] These methods are usually called J-resolved spectroscopy, but are sometimes also known as chemical shift resolved spectroscopy or δ-resolved spectroscopy.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] They are useful for analysing molecules for which the 1D-NMR spectra contain overlapping multiplets as the J-resolved spectrum vertically displaces the multiplet from each nucleus by a different amount.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Each peak in the 2D spectrum will have the same horizontal coordinate that it has in a non-decoupled 1D spectrum, but its vertical coordinate will be the chemical shift of the single peak that the nucleus has in a decoupled 1D spectrum.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] For the heteronuclear version, the simplest pulse sequence used is called a Müller–Kumar–Ernst (MKE) experiment, which has a single 90° pulse for the heteronucleus for the preparation period, no mixing period, and applies a decoupling signal to the proton during the detection period.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] There are several variants on this pulse sequence which are more sensitive and more accurate, which fall under the categories of *gated decoupler methods* and *spin-flip methods*.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Homonuclear J-resolved spectroscopy uses the spin echo pulse sequence.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] 3D and 4D experiments can also be done, sometimes by running the pulse sequences from two or three 2D experiments in series.
[src:protein-nmr/two-dimensional-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-spectroscopy] Many of the commonly used 3D experiments, however, are triple resonance experiments; examples include the HNCA and HNCOCA experiments, which are often used in protein NMR.
